      "params_detail": {},
      "score": 0.0,
      "raw_content": "In Japanese, there are several ways to say \"goodbye\" depending on the context and level of formality:\n\n## Common Ways to Say Goodbye\n\n| Japanese | Romaji | Meaning/Usage |\n|----------|-------|---------------|\n| **\u3055\u3088\u3046\u306a\u3089** | *say\u014dnara* | The most common, direct translation of \"goodbye\" |\n| **\u3058\u3083\u3042** | *jaa* | Casual, informal \"see you later\" or \"bye\" |\n| **\u307e\u305f\u306d** | *mata ne* | \"See you again\" or \"see you later\" |\n| **\u304a\u5143\u6c17\u3067** | *ogenki de* | \"Take care\" (polite/formal) |\n| **\u5931\u793c\u3057\u307e\u3059** | *shitsurei shimasu* | \"I'll be rude now\" (when leaving a formal situation) |\n\n## Quick Tips\n\n- **\u3055\u3088\u3046\u306a\u3089** is safe to use in almost any situation\n- **\u307e\u305f\u306d** is friendly and implies you'll meet again\n- **\u304a\u5143\u6c17\u3067** is polite and shows consideration for the other person's well-being\n- **\u5931\u793c\u3057\u307e\u3059** is used when you're leaving a meeting, event, or formal gathering\n\nWould you like to know more about any of these expressions or how to use them in specific situations?",
